Issue 76. vertical-align ambiguities B
Comment: http://www.w3.org/mid/3F833074.32375.922D24@localhost
Comment: http://www.w3.org/mid/20031007195251.GA5491@darby.dbaron.org
Comment: http://www.w3.org/mid/3F85B43E.12760.2B3E50@localhost
Comment: http://lists.w3.org/Archives/Public/www-style/1999Mar/0121.html
  "indeterminate cases"
http://dbaron.org/css/2000/01/dibm
| CSS does not fully describe the result if the tallest (in full
| height) loose element in the line is not the root of the line. This
| is what I mean by an indeterminate case.
| ...
| I think the best would be to treat the largest element (in full
| height) as the root of the line (that is, to place it first), and
| place the root element of the line as if it had the alignment of the
| largest loose element (which is either top or bottom).
...where 'full height', 'loose', 'root of the line' are defined as in
http://lists.w3.org/Archives/Public/www-style/1999Mar/0121.html
(I think this is equivalent to saying that you position the root of
the line, then place the biggest loose subtree according to its
alignment, then place the other loose subtrees in the resulting space,
then (vertically) shrink wrap the line box around that and stack it in
with the other line boxes. -- Hixie)

Resolution: Leave undefined in 2.1.
Reply: http://www.w3.org/mid/16426.37679.742180.198872@lanalana.inria.fr
Issue closed.
