Issue 123. http://www.w3.org/mid/3F8E49FF.A8ABAA98@i18nguy.com
| Does ':lang()' match elements that have language set to the empty
| tag?
|
| It might be thought to match all languages, since in the absence of
| simple selectors, * is presumed, so it is conceivable that absence
| of a tag might be equivalent to all. It might also be deemed to be
| an error to have no tag inside the parens.
|
| So the spec should address the issue.
Reply: http://www.w3.org/mid/16270.39061.194849.106208@lanalana.inria.fr

Resolution: Make :lang() undefined in 2.1 (we'll define in CSS3+) In
addition, specify that :lang()'s argument must be an identifier as it
says in the grammar. This also needs changing the grammar to allow
function-like pseudo-classes with null arguments.
Document updated.
Reply: http://www.w3.org/mid/16427.61526.604998.374365@lanalana.inria.fr
Issue closed.
