------------------------------------------------------------------------
Issue 219. "block level elements" is sometimes used to mean
block+table and sometimes to mean block + table-cell

Tantek says:

Yes this could be a problem.

Essentially the distinction is outer-block-level-ness and
inner-block-level-ness, e.g.

 display      block-level-ness (if any)
 -------------------------------------
 block        inner and outer
 list-item    inner and outer
 table        outer
 table-cell   inner
 inline-block inner

I believe "block level elements" is used nearly always to mean "outer
block level" but there are probably some instances where it really
means "inner block level". Not sure how to resolve this.

Perhaps we should simply leave this as is and address specific
instances as we find them (e.g. if "block level element" is used in a
context where table vs. table-cell makes a difference, we can point
that out).

Notes from meeting: How to resolve this for table-cells and
   inline-blocks and table-captions: Imagine the same situation with
   an anonymous block box immediately inside the table cell containing
   all its children -- the rendering should be the same.

Resolution: Solve individual cases (see below) and rely on editors to
find further cases.

Resolution 1:
   For line-height, change "If the property is set on a block-level
   element whose content" to "If the property is set on a block-level,
   table-cell, table-caption or inline-block element whose content".

Resolution 2:
   For vertical-align, change "or to the strut of a parent block-level
   element." to "or to the strut of a parent block-level, table-cell,
   table-caption or inline-block element."

Resolution 3:
   :first-line pseudo-element should apply to block-level, table-cell,
   table-caption or inline-block.

Resolution 4:
   Definition of bidi-override, second sentence, reword to: For
   block-level, table-cell, table-caption, or inline-block elements
   this creates an override for inline-level descendents not within
   another block-level, table-cell, table-caption, or inline-block
   element.

Resolution 5:
   Editors to check their chapters for occurances of the term "block
   level" to ensure the above criteria are met.
    --  http://www.w3.org/mid/BC52B345.3647F%25tantek@cs.stanford.edu

Document updated.
Issue closed.
------------------------------------------------------------------------
