Issue 225. Where does a float between two blocks go? The current text
contradicts itself (defines it as being at the bottom of the last line
box or the top of the (common) containing block, then says it is
undefined and should be positioned at a place between collapsed
margins). We could change rule 5 in section 9.5 to read:

5. The outer top of a floating box may not be higher than the outer
   top of any block or floated box generated by an element earlier in
   the source document<ins>, and may not be higher than the bottom padding
   edge of any earlier block-level sibling</ins>.

...or add a new rule after rule 5 to mention that, or we could move
the text after the rules to be before the rules, or be the first rule,
and change the text to read:

0. When the float occurs between two collapsing margins, the float is
   positioned as if it had an otherwise empty anonymous block parent
   taking part in the flow. The position of such a parent is defined
   by the rules in the section on margin collapsing. This block then
   becomes the containing block for the float in the rules below.

See also:
  http://www.w3.org/mid/20031121002240.GA25096@darby.dbaron.org
  http://www.w3.org/mid/A23328EA-1BBA-11D8-BE2C-000A958E6110@apple.com

Note: This is technically editorial (We already agreed to the change,
we just got the wording too wooly. Our sheep would be proud.)

Resolution: Take the paragraph after the rules in section 9.5 Floats
("When the rules above do not result in an exact vertical position, as
may be the case when the float occurs between two collapsing margins,
the float is positioned as if it had an otherwise empty anonymous
block parent taking part in the flow. The position of such a parent is
defined by the rules in the section on margin collapsing.") and move
it to the end of rule 4, then edit the first bit of this text (up to
the second comma) to read "When the float occurs between two
collapsing margins".

Document updated.
Issue closed.
------------------------------------------------------------------------
Issue 226. Line boxes shrink to make room for floats... do we want to
say they make room for the outer edge of a float? If not, earlier
content can have to move out of the way of later floats, which is a
circular dependency. We appear to have lost the note saying that
behaviour for negative margins on floats is undefined. (It doesn't
need to be, the most sensible, IMHO, behavour is to define things per
the outer edge as we have for the rules.)

Tantek suggests: "negative margins for floats may not necessarily
display earlier content"

Ian says: I'd rather just say it shouldn't (i.e. "use the margin
box"). It seems much more predictable, a LOT easier to implement, and
actually more useful for authors who want to have that kind of effect.
For example, Eric's book has examples where he puts negative margins
on floats that would get broken if we let UAs wrap around the border
edge instead.

Tantek later agreed with Ian.

David and Bert also agree.

Resolution: Change "However, line boxes created next to the float are
shortened to make room for the floated box" to "However, line boxes
created next to the float are shortened to make room for the margin
box of the float". (adds "for the margin box of" remove trailing "ed
box".)
Document updated.
Issue closed.
------------------------------------------------------------------------
