Issue 229. http://www.w3.org/mid/20031116221647.GA15866@darby.dbaron.org
| I think the CSS 2.1 exit criteria need to be revised to take this into
| account.  (I wasn't previously aware that you considered the error
| handling rules applicable to a feature not to be part of that feature.)

(i.e. do we need a way to say that unless a UA pass all the error
handling tests of the test suite, it doesn't count? Or do we need a
way to say that a feature that for a feature to pass, we have to have
interoperability on its forward-compatibility parsability as well as
its implementation?)

See also: http://www.w3.org/mid/Pine.LNX.4.58.0311162257160.3009@dhalsim.dreamhost.com
See also: http://lists.w3.org/Archives/Member/w3c-css-wg/2003OctDec/0200.html
See alse: http://www.w3.org/mid/Pine.LNX.4.58.0311170614520.3009@dhalsim.dreamhost.com

Tantek says: In general, I think this kind of criteria is too harsh
for 2.1, or even the CSS3 drafts which are in CR or passed LC. I think
perhaps the first CSS draft that should consider making use of such
criteria should be CSS3 Syntax (or whatever we rename it to).

Resolution:
  * Require that all UAs report results for all error handling tests.
  * UAs that fail error handling tests will not block that feature.
Issue closed.
