Issue 244. What does "generic notion of newline" mean wrt bidi?

Specifically, <br> is supposed to be equivalent to U+2028 LINE
SEPARATOR (HTML4 9.3.2.1), which is bidi class WS (whitespace
neutral), while U+000A is class B (paragraph separator).

But we say line breaks occur "where necessary" for automatic line
wrapping and "at occurances of \A" and "newlines in the source". We
also say that "\A is the generic concept of a newline" in CSS.

So how do you, in a pure CSS UA, implement the <br> element in CSS?

Are \A-style-newlines in generated content bidi class B? Presumably the
"needed" newlines are class WS?

Ref: http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr9/#Bidirectional_Character_Types

Tantek:
| I am not a bidi expert so I'm not sure how to evaluate this issue.
| How do bidi UAs implement <br> in terms of CSS?

Ian:
| Badly. IIRC, WinIE does it per CSS, Mozilla does it per HTML, and
| Opera does something stupid (treats it as a line break and LRO or
| something).

Resolution: No change. Ian to examine this for CSS3 Text.
Issue closed.
