Issue 264.
The spec contradicts itself over whether IDs can start with digits or
not. In particular, prose in 4.1.3 and the grammar in section 4 and
appendix G.

tantek proposes: http://www.w3.org/mid/BC32D85B.346F3%25tantek@cs.stanford.edu
dbaron disagrees: http://www.w3.org/mid/20040120212517.GA6242@darby.dbaron.org
Bjoern Hoehrmann says: http://www.w3.org/mid/4047c522.347257379@smtp.bjoern.hoehrmann.de

Resolution:

First, in 4.1.3 "Characters and case", just after "they cannot start
with a digit.", add: "Only properties, values, units, pseudo-classes,
pseudo-elements, and at-rules may start with a hyphen (-); other
identifiers (e.g. element names, classes, or IDs) may not."

Second, change 5.9 "ID selectors" from "A CSS ID selector contains a
"#" immediately followed by the ID value." to "A CSS ID selector
contains a "#" immediately followed by the ID value, which must be an
identifier."

Third, change the following sentence in Appendix G:

   A conforming UA must also adhere to the forward-compatible parsing
   rules, the property and value notation, and the unit notation.

...to this:

   A conforming UA must also adhere to the forward-compatible parsing
   rules, the selectors notation, the property and value notation, and
   the unit notation.

Documented updated.
Issue closed.
------------------------------------------------------------------------
Issue 265. null bytes and \0 - \000000 should be parsing errors.
   http://www.w3.org/mid/200401161857.42942.bert@w3.org

What kind of parsing errors, exactly? Same as an unexpected character,
rendering the current token invalid and causing the declaration or
rule to be ignored?

tantek:

Proposed resolution:

Add a sentence to Appendix G prohibiting null bytes and \0 - \000000.  The
presence of any such character makes the style sheet invalid.

Per the resolution to issue 258, leave it undefined/unspecified what
implementations should do with such a style sheet, and specify it in CSS3
Syntax.

[Agreement with Bert via IRC]

Resolution: In third bullet point of 4.1.3 "Characters and case",
replace "character with that number" with "character with that number,
which must not be zero".
Document updated.
Issue closed.
